post_text: The WIAA Executive Board took action on Tuesday to modify the 2020-21 WIAA sports season calendar in light of the COVID-19 pandemic. The changes will create four WIAA-sanctioned seasons and will also move moderate- and high-risk team sports, originally scheduled for the fall season, to the WIAA Season 3. Learn more on the WIAA website.

text:
The WIAA Executive Board took action on Tuesday to modify the 2020-21 WIAA sports season calendar in light of the COVID-19 pandemic. The changes will create four WIAA-sanctioned seasons and will also move moderate- and high-risk team sports, originally scheduled for the fall season, to the WIAA Season 3. Learn more on the WIAA website.

The Northshore School District fully supports the freedom of our community members to have their voices heard, especially in light of the horrific death of George Floyd in Minneapolis. Our understanding is that there are community-planned demonstrations taking place across areas of our district this afternoon. Please note that all Northshore campuses are closed to the public.

We see you. We hear you. Stay safe

post_text:
After a great deal of research, conversations at the national and state level, and meetings with our District leadership and education partners, we have developed Northshore Learns v. 2.0 distance learning. This latest model will provide the best possible experience for students, families and educators who are delivering the instruction while caring for themselves and their own families in a situation that is anything but normal.

Dr. Reid will share more details about Northshore Learns v. 2.0 before noon on Thursday, March 26.

Visit our website to learn more about remote learning and student access to devices.

Political campaigning or commercial solicitations

ðŸ”’ In the coming weeks, classroom locks at Arrowhead and Kenmore elementaries will be upgraded. The new locks can be locked from inside the classroom without use of a key, while the old locks required someone to lock the door from the outside with a key. The new locks also have a visual indicator which will help in an emergency situation.

These safety upgrades were made possible by the generous support of our Northshore community who approved the 2018 bond.

These are the final two schools in the pilot program for lock upgrades. Northshore and Kenmore middle schools had their locks upgraded during the spring and summer. The goal is for all main classroom entry locks to be upgraded districtwide by the end of next calendar year, with 19 additional schools soon to be under contract for completion by the end of summer 2020!

This week the field project at Northshore Middle School was completed! While the field opened for use two weeks ago, minor remaining items were completed this week. The project began over the summer and included re-sodding the football field with natural grass to improve drainage, refreshing the high jump, long jump and shot put areas, and installing new sprinkler heads and the controller. The football field goal posts and soccer goals were also refurbished.

Thank you to our generous Northshore voters who approved the 2018 bond, which made this improvement project possible!

The playground improvements at Sunrise Elementary are complete and the playground is open! The upper field walkway had some large roots removed to improve safety. Following this removal, a new root barrier and new sidewalk were installed, leading to the covered play area. Additionally, the long jump pit was refurbished.

The lower playground also had intrusive roots removed from the asphalt and new pavement installed. A root barrier and new drainage pipes were installed.

Thank you to the generous Northshore voters who approved the 2018 bond, which made these much needed playground improvements possible.

post_text:
Safety and drainage improvements are in progress at Sunrise Elementaryâ€™s playground. Roots that were in the walkway leading to the covered play area on the upper field are being removed, and a root barrier and new concrete sidewalk are being installed. The long jump pit is being refurbished. The full upper field is slated to be open by the start of school.

Improvements on the lower playground will include removal of asphalt and intrusive roots that are bulging the asphalt. Also, a root barrier and new drainage pipes will be installed, as well as new pavement poured. The work on the lower playground is scheduled to be completed in mid-September.

This much needed playground improvement project is made possible by the generous Northshore voters who approved the 2018 bond.

Throughout the summer, a number of much needed building improvements were made at Lockwood Elementary. The school was re-roofed, the heating system was replaced, and classroom lighting was upgraded. The project is now substantially complete with a few remaining items, some of which include final permit inspections, boiler system start up and checks and cleaning operations. Once permit inspections are complete staff can begin to move back into their classrooms. These necessary improvements were made possible by the generous support of Northshore voters who approved the 2018 bond.

The timing of the building improvements hindered Lockwoodâ€™s ability to participate in this yearâ€™s Community Serve Day. However, Northshoreâ€™s Capital Projects team and the contractor are arranging to clean and update the campus landscaping, assist teachers with moving in, and ensure the campus looks great for the upcoming school year.

This summer Northshore Middle Schoolâ€™s field will see many improvements which include: re-sodding the football field with natural grass to improve drainage, refreshing the high jump, long jump and shot put areas, and installing new sprinkler heads and the controller. The football field goal posts and soccer goals will also be refurbished.

To date, demolition and field prep is complete. New sod will be placed this week and it will take at least a few weeks for the sod to take root before the field can be used.

This improvement project was made possible by the generous support of our Northshore community with their vote of approval on the 2018 bond!

post_text:
Tennis courts at Bothell High School are being upgraded this summer to new post-tensioned concrete courts. The old fencing and posts will be removed and new fencing, nets and players benches will be installed.

Demolition and site prep is nearly complete, with holes being drilled for fence and post footings. Once complete, the crew will begin a soil fill layer between the old and new courts. The courts are scheduled to be completed in late September.

Thank you to the Northshore community for voting to approve the 2018 bond, which made these upgrades possible at Bothell High!

post_text:
Woodinville High Schoolâ€™s tennis courts and softball field are being upgraded this summer. Construction began in mid-July and is scheduled to be completed in late September. These projects are currently in the demolition phase. The old tennis posts and fences are being removed, as is the infield turf and outfield grass.

The tennis courts will have new post-tensioned concrete courts installed on top of the existing courts. New fencing, nets and player benches will also be installed.

New turf will be installed in the infield of the softball field, and new synthetic turf will be put in the outfield. The field will also have new batting cages installed.

Both of these projects at Woodinville High School are made possible through the 2018 bond, which was approved by our generous Northshore community!
